# emmc-monitor-mqtt

Lightweight Python MQTT monitor for eMMC/CPU/memory/storage on Linux devices. Publishes Home Assistant discovery topics, LWT, and key system metrics with physical interface detection. Docker-ready for easy deployment via Portainer or docker-compose.

---

## Features

- Reports eMMC lifetime and health flags  
- Root filesystem used percentage and free space  
- Memory usage (used/free)  
- CPU temperature, governor, and min/max frequency  
- Host IP (diagnostic entity)  
- Home Assistant auto-discovery compatible  
- LWT (Last Will & Testament) support  
- Lightweight Docker image for Linux devices  

---

## Requirements

- Linux device with Python 3.11+  
- MQTT broker accessible from the device (e.g., Mosquitto, Home Assistant)  

---

## Environment Variables

| Variable      | Default                    | Description |
|---------------|---------------------------|-------------|
| `MQTT_HOST`   | `homeassistant.local`     | MQTT broker hostname/IP |
| `MQTT_PORT`   | `1883`                     | MQTT broker port |
| `MQTT_USER`   | None                       | MQTT username (optional) |
| `MQTT_PASS`   | None                       | MQTT password (optional) |
| `DEVICE_NAME` | `HA remote helper 01`      | Friendly device name |
| `ROOT_FS_PATH` | `/`                       | Filesystem path to inspect for rootfs metrics; set to a bind-mounted host path in Docker |

---

## Docker

Pull the latest image:

```bash
docker pull ghcr.io/bennydiamond/emmc-monitor-mqtt/emmc-monitor:latest

To report host root filesystem usage from inside Docker, bind-mount the host root filesystem read-only and set `ROOT_FS_PATH` to that mount point, for example `/hostfs`.

